1.title: Pot Luck
1.plot: Louie goes to a pot luck dinner for the parents in Lily's class, but ends up going to the wrong party. When he finally reaches the right party, he has an unusual encounter with the surrogate mother of the couple hosting the dinner.

2.title: A La Carte
2.plot: An urgent matter cuts Louie's grocery trip short. Louie gives some frank advice to a struggling amateur during Open Mic Night. Pamela and Louie try to set the parameters of their relationship.

3.title: Cop Story
3.plot: Louie has an uncomfortable evening with a police officer who was once engaged to his sister.

4.title: Bobby's House
4.plot: Louie goes to a wake with his brother. Louie gets beat up on the street by a woman. Pamela gives Louie a makeover to mask his injuries so he can perform on stage.

5.title: Untitled
5.plot: After taking Jane to the doctor and picking Lilly up from a sitter, Louie begins having horrific recurring nightmares that he can't escape from.

6.title: Sleepover
6.plot: Louie is upset when he sees Lily texting in the middle of a Broadway play. Louie hosts a birthday slumber party for Jane, but it is interrupted by two unexpected phone calls.

7.title: The Road: Part 1
7.plot: Louie goes on the road and is stuck in Cincinnati in a bad hotel with talkative driver. He then loses his carry-on bag at the Atlanta airport while helping a lost child.

8.title: The Road: Part 2
8.plot: Louie's road trip continues in Oklahoma City, where's he's stuck sharing a condo with an crude, obnoxious opening act who tells a bunch of fart jokes.

1.title: Pilot
1.plot: Louie goes on a date as well as a field trip with his daughters. Both go badly.

2.title: Poker/Divorce
2.plot: Louie and his friends have a discussion about homosexuality with a gay friend during a poker game. After Louie's divorce is finalized, he looks up a woman he had a "moment" with back in school.

3.title: Dr. Ben/Nick
3.plot: Louie goes to the doctor and argues with an old friend.

4.title: So Old/Playdate
4.plot: Louie's age is an advantage and he sets up a play date.

5.title: Travel Day/South
5.plot: Louie goes on a trip. Louie plays the South.

6.title: Heckler/Cop Movie
6.plot: Louie reluctantly acts in a movie.

7.title: Double Date/Mom
7.plot: Louie's brother comes to him with an odd request related to his date, and Louie's mom comes to tell him that she is a lesbian.

8.title: Dogpound
8.plot: While the kids are away, Louie eats a lot of ice cream, gets high with a neighbor, and rescues an old dog from the pound.

9.title: Bully
9.plot: Louie recalls his awkward sex education lessons as a child, and a high school bully threatens Louie in a donut shop and ruins his date.

10.title: Dentist/Tarese
10.plot: Louie tries to overcome his fear of dentists, and tries to get a date with an African American grocery cashier.

11.title: God
11.plot: Louie recalls a traumatic lesson from Catholic school about Jesus dying for his sins.

12.title: Gym
12.plot: Louie fantasizes about a TV news anchor, and winds up in the hospital after working out with his new personal trainer.

13.title: Night Out
13.plot: Louie goes out for the night.

1.title: Pregnant
1.plot: Louie gets a surprise visit from his pregnant sister, who has to be rushed to the hospital in the middle of the night with severe pains.

2.title: Bummer/Blueberries
2.plot: Louie witnesses a bum's death on his way to a date, and gets propositioned for casual sex by a single mom at his daughter's school.

3.title: Moving
3.plot: Louie has trouble finding a nice apartment, and when he finally finds a home he wants to buy, it is impossibly out of his price range.

4.title: Joan
4.plot: Louie quits a lounge gig at an Atlantic City casino after a bad night and winds up hanging out with Joan Rivers.

5.title: Country Drive
5.plot: When Louis decides to visit his great aunt, he takes his kids on a country drive to visit her. But when he arrives his kids and him notice her past self and devastating news.

6.title: Subway/Pamela
6.plot: Louie rides the subway and hangs out with his friend.

7.title: Oh Louie/Tickets
7.plot: Louie remembers his past career failures and tries to get concert tickets for his daughter.

8.title: Come On, God
8.plot: Louie explores one of his lifelong habits.

9.title: Eddie
9.plot: Louie reunites with an old friend.

10.title: Halloween/Ellie
10.plot: Halloween is in the air and Louis and his kids go trick or treating. But when they go trick or treating, Louis and his kids meet some very bad people, in which Louis has to fend off to protect him and his kids.

11.title: Duckling
11.plot: Louie leaves for Afghanistan to entertain the troops, but he doesn't know that one of his daughters left him a surprise in his suitcase.

12.title: Niece
12.plot: Louie takes care of his niece while her mother leaves for Philadelphia, but he has no idea how to communicate with her.

13.title: New Jersey/Airport
13.plot: Louie has a pretty bad time in general.

1.title: Something Is Wrong
1.plot: Louie breaks up with his new love interest, gets his car destroyed by a construction crew, buys a new motorcycle, and winds up in the hospital.

2.title: Telling Jokes/Set Up
2.plot: Louie agrees to dinner at a comedian friend's house, not knowing that he is about to be set up on a date.

3.title: Miami
3.plot: Louie goes to Miami, makes friends with a Cuban-American lifeguard, and decides to extend the trip to hang out with him a little longer--leading to an awkward conversation.

4.title: Daddy's Girlfriend: Part 1
4.plot: After Louie's kids put pressure him to find a girlfriend, he finds a potential prospect at the local bookstore.

5.title: Daddy's Girlfriend: Part 2
5.plot: Louie goes out on an adventurous first date with the woman he met at the bookstore.

6.title: Barney/Never
6.plot: Louie has lunch and goes to a strip club with a man he meets at a friend's gravesite, and babysits for a friend's socially-awkward son.

7.title: Ikea/Piano Lesson
7.plot: Louie takes an awkward shopping trip with a female acquaintance, Louie gets some disturbing news from a different woman during a piano lesson, and Louie tries to make amends with an old friend.

8.title: Dad
8.plot: After his uncle visits and tells him to go to Boston to see his father, Louie breaks out and begins throwing up.

9.title: Looking for Liz/Lilly Changes
9.plot: Louie learns that Liz no longer works at the bookstore, and her replacement employee helps Louie try to find her; Louie calls the police after Jane tells him that Lilly left home.

10.title: Late Show: Part 1
10.plot: Louie takes advantage of an incredible opportunity on The Tonight Show and gets a potential job offer afterwards that could change his life.

11.title: Late Show: Part 2
11.plot: Louie's "training" gets off to a rough start as he prepares for his chance to audition for David Letterman's job.

12.title: Late Show: Part 3
12.plot: Right before Louie shoots his talk show pilot, Jerry Seinfeld comes to him some surprising news.

13.title: New Year's Eve
13.plot: Louie is alone after Christmas and has a traumatic New Year's Eve, so he decides to get away from it all--in China.

1.title: Back
1.plot: Louie injures his back while shopping for a vibrator.

2.title: Model
2.plot: Louie has a horrible night introducing Jerry Seinfeld for a benefit in the Hamptons, but his luck changes when he runs into a model who actually liked his act.

3.title: So Did the Fat Lady
3.plot: A fat woman who works at the comedy club keeps asking Louie out on a date, but Louie is not interested.

4.title: Elevator: Part 1
4.plot: Louie freaks out when he loses Jane on the subway; Louie helps out a woman in his building who gets stuck in the elevator.

5.title: Elevator: Part 2
5.plot: Louie's visit to the woman who got stuck in the elevator is interrupted when Jane gets in trouble at school; Louie takes an interest in the elevator woman's niece, Amia.

6.title: Elevator: Part 3
6.plot: An old flame returns to New York, but Louie rejects her because he is interested in Amia, who then comes to him with some bad news. Louie and his ex have a meeting at school about Jane.

7.title: Elevator: Part 4
7.plot: Louie and Janet spend the day together and issues arise, issues like their kids, their divorce, and Louie's life in its whole. Also, Louie has a flashback surrounding his and his ex-wife's marriage.

8.title: Elevator: Part 5
8.plot: Louie's friend, Todd Barry, tells a hilarious story about the events of his day; Louie is torn about taking his relationship with Amia to the next level even though she is about to leave.

9.title: Elevator: Part 6
9.plot: The tension between Louie and Amia after they sleep together is put on hold when Louie has to save his kids and ex-wife from the hurricane.

10.title: Pamela: Part 1
10.plot: Still heartbroken over losing Amia, Louie turns to Pamela to see if her offer still stands.

11.title: In the Woods: Part 1
11.plot: When Louie catches Lily smoking pot, he flashes back to a similar period from his own childhood.

12.title: In the Woods: Part 2
12.plot: Young Louie's drug problem begins to escalate, and he must eventually face the consequences of his actions.

13.title: Pamela: Part 2
13.plot: Louie talks Pamela into going out on a date with him, but will it end in just more frustration?

14.title: Pamela: Part 3
14.plot: Pamela and Louie's daughters, Lilly and Jane, hit it off from the start. She also gets to meet Janet, Louie's ex-wife. After a nice afternoon and a less nice evening, Louie confesses his love to Pamela but doesn't get the reaction he wants.

_Louie_ (qv) is a stand-up comedian and divorced father of two girls. This series follows him through his everyday life, as he meets various characters, struggles with his love life and pursues humor.::Anonymous
synopsis: Louis C.K. writes, directs and stars in this show about a stand-up comedian, mostly performing late night shows at small clubs and restaurants. He is a single father living with his two school-going daughters. Episodes focus on events in his everyday life, and are bookended by clips from his stand-up routine. C.K. is the only regular in the show, and even his daughters are portrayed by more than one actor. The style of humor is often sexual and racist, with occasional use of vulgar language. C.K. exercises total freedom in the episodes he creates and there are few boundaries established throughout the show, with episodes dealing with such diverse topics as picking up the kids from school to doing drugs at his next-door neighbor's. Most of his stand-up routines mirror his real life and often have little or no association with the topic of the episode.
